 <H1>Decomposition of a Relation Scheme</H1> 
 <P><UL>
<LI><H2>Suppose that relation R contains attributes A1 ... An.  A decomposition of R consists of replacing R by two or more relations such that:
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Each new relation scheme contains a subset of the attributes of R (and no attributes that do not appear in R), and
<LI>Every attribute of R appears as an attribute of one of the new relations.
</UL></UL><UL>
<LI><H2>Intuitively, decomposing R means we will store instances of the relation schemes produced by the decomposition, instead of instances of R.
</H2>
</UL><UL>
<LI><H2>E.g.,  Can decompose SNLRWH into SNLRH and RW.</H2>
</UL></P>
